## 9. Siamese Architecture {#9-siamese-architecture}

### What is a Siamese network?

A **Siamese network** uses the **same model with shared weights** to process two inputs, then compares their outputs. Both inputs go through *identical* processing.

In your case — [SiameseEGNN](file:///c:/Users/test2/Downloads/TEST/models/egnn.py#L221-L353):

```
Protein A → [Input Projector → EGNN → Attention Pool → Projector → L2 Norm] → Embedding A
Protein B → [SAME network, SAME weights]                                     → Embedding B

Similarity = cosine_similarity(Embedding A, Embedding B)
```

### Why Siamese?

You want to **compare** two proteins. A Siamese network ensures both proteins are embedded into the **same feature space** using the **same transformation**, so their cosine similarity is meaningful.

### The full forward pass — [forward_one()](file:///c:/Users/test2/Downloads/TEST/models/egnn.py#L287-L325)

```
1. ESM-2 input [N, 320] → Input Projector MLP → [N, 64]    (dimension reduction)
2. [N, 64] → 4x EGNN Layers → [N, 64]                       (message passing)
3. [N, 64] → Attention Pool → [1, 64]                        (graph → vector)
4. [1, 64] → Projector MLP → [1, 256]                        (embedding space)
5. [1, 256] → L2 Normalize → [1, 256]                        (unit hypersphere)
```

### What is L2 normalization?

```python
z = F.normalize(z, p=2, dim=-1)  # z / ||z||
```

This projects all embeddings onto the **unit hypersphere** (all vectors have length 1). This ensures that cosine similarity is always in [-1, 1] and that the magnitude of the embedding doesn't affect comparison — only the **direction** matters.

