## 20. Killer Questions a Judge Will Ask {#20-killer-questions}

### Mathematics

**Q: "Explain SE(3)-equivariance mathematically."**
> "If R is a rotation matrix and t is a translation vector, an SE(3)-equivariant function f satisfies: f(Rx + t) = Rf(x) + t for coordinates, and f(Rx + t) = f(x) for scalar features. Our EGNN achieves this because coordinate updates use the direction vector (x_i - x_j) which transforms as R(x_i - x_j) under rotation, multiplied by a scalar weight computed from rotation-invariant quantities (distances). Node features are computed entirely from distances, which are invariant."

**Q: "How does InfoNCE relate to mutual information?"**
> "InfoNCE is a lower bound on the mutual information between the anchor and positive sample representations. Maximizing InfoNCE maximizes the mutual information, encouraging the model to capture all shared information between different views of the same data."

**Q: "Why soft-margin instead of hard-margin triplet loss?"**
> "Hard-margin triplet loss has gradient = 0 once the margin is satisfied. In our case with 29 pairs, the model can satisfy the margin quickly, causing training to plateau. Soft-margin (log1p(exp(...))) asymptotically approaches 0 but never reaches it, ensuring gradient signal flows throughout all 200 epochs."

### Architecture

**Q: "Why not just use a standard CNN on the protein structure?"**
> "CNNs operate on regular grids (images). Proteins are irregular 3D point clouds. GNNs operate directly on graph structure, which naturally represents protein topology. Furthermore, CNNs are not rotation-equivariant by default—you'd need massive data augmentation, whereas our EGNN has equivariance built into the architecture itself."

**Q: "Your cross-attention is disabled in forward_one. Why keep it?"**
> "Our ablation study showed that cross-attention caused dimensional collapse (18.8% vs 68.8% Top-3 without it). The ESM-2 features are already processed through the input projector, and the EGNN captures sequence information implicitly through these projected features. The cross-attention module remains in the architecture for future investigation with different training strategies."

### Validation

**Q: "29 pairs is a small dataset. How do you avoid overfitting?"**
> "Five strategies: (1) Leave-one-out cross-validation proves generalization to held-out pairs. (2) Blind validation on 6 completely unseen pairs achieves 100%/100% sensitivity/specificity. (3) Dropout (0.2) and weight decay (1e-4) regularize the model. (4) Rotation augmentation creates infinite training views from each pair. (5) Early stopping with patience=40 prevents overtraining."

**Q: "How do you know the discoveries are real?"**
> "We don't—they're computational predictions. That's why we call them 'candidate interactions' and 'hypothesis generation.' The value is that they're testable: a virologist could experimentally validate SARS-CoV-2 Spike → TNFR1 interaction using co-immunoprecipitation or surface plasmon resonance."

### Technical Details

**Q: "What's the computational cost? Can this scale?"**
> "Processing one protein takes ~2-5 seconds (ESM-2 embedding + graph construction + EGNN forward pass). Comparing two proteins is two forward passes + one cosine similarity. Scanning 8 viral proteins × 15 human proteins = 120 comparisons takes ~10 minutes on CPU. This scales linearly."

**Q: "Why ESM-2 t6 (8M params) and not t33 (650M params)?"**
> "The t6 model is small enough to run on CPU without a GPU, making the tool accessible to labs without expensive hardware. The 320-dimensional embeddings capture sufficient biochemical context for our task. Upgrading to t33 would give 1280-dim embeddings and potentially better performance, but at the cost of requiring GPU acceleration."
